<chapter xml:id="chapter-log" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Logarithmic growth</title>

<section xml:id="section-log-definition">
<title>The natural logarithm</title>

<p>
<xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power" /> tells us how to calculate a quantity's accumulation for any rate model that is a power of <m>t</m>,
<em>except</em> for the special case of <m>r(t) = t^{-1}</m>.
It turns out there is no simple formula for the accumulation for this special rate function,
so we will have to resort to using integral notation to represent it.
For convenience, we will also give this special accumulation function a name.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-log-natural">
	<title>Natural logarithm</title>
	<p>
	The function that returns the accumulation for a quantity that is varying according to rate function <m>r(t) = 1/t</m>,
	relative to <q>initial</q> time <m>t = 1</m>:
	<me> \ln t = \ccmint{1}{t}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </me>.
	</p>
</definition>

<figure xml:id="figure-log-positive-values">
	<caption>The natural logarithm as accumulation under <m>r(t) = 1/t</m>.</caption>

	<sidebyside valign="middle"> <!-- widths="" margins=""  -->

		<figure>
			<caption>An accumulation under <m>r(t) = 1/t</m>.</caption>
			<image width="45%">
				<description>An area under <m>r(t) = 1/t</m>.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="log.d/log-accumulation-positive.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<figure xml:id="figure-log-positive-values-height">
			<caption>The corresponding accumulation value.</caption>
			<image width="45%">
				<description>The corresponding value on the graph of <m>\ln t</m>.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="log.d/log-value-positive.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

	</sidebyside>

</figure>

<p>
In <xref ref="figure-log-positive-values" />,
the height of the logarithm function's graph on the right at the input <m>t</m> corresponds to the magnitude of the shaded blue area under the graph of the rate function <m>r(t) = 1/t</m> on the left.
</p>

<p>
Notice that the graph of the logarithm function in <xref ref="figure-log-positive-values-height" /> shows negative accumulation values for <m>0 \lt t \lt 1</m>.
This is because of <xref ref="convention-integ-definite-props-backwards" text="type-local">Property</xref> in <xref ref="convention-integ-definite-props" /> <mdash />
if we allow time to <q>run backwards</q>,
then we consider the quantity to be dissipating instead of accumulating,
so that <me> \ln t = \ccmint{1}{t}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </me>
for <m>0 \lt t \lt 1</m> is the <em>negative</em> of the accumulation that occurs over time interval <m> t \le u \le 1 </m>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-log-negative-values">
	<caption>The natural logarithm as accumulation under <m>r(t) = 1/t</m>.</caption>
	<sidebyside valign="middle"> <!-- widths="" margins=""  -->
		<figure>
			<caption>A <q>reverse</q> accumulation under <m>r(t) = 1/t</m>.</caption>
			<image width="45%">
				<description>An area under <m>r(t) = 1/t</m>.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="log.d/log-accumulation-negative.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
		<figure xml:id="figure-log-negative-values-height">
			<caption>The corresponding negative accumulation value.</caption>
			<image width="45%">
				<description>The corresponding value on the graph of <m>\ln t</m>.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="log.d/log-value-negative.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
	</sidebyside>
</figure>

<example xml:id="example-log-definite-integral">
	<title>Using the natural logarithm to represent integral values</title>
	<p>
	Suppose we would like to calculate
	<me> \ccmint{3}{4}{ t + \frac{1}{t} }{t} </me>.
	Similarly to <xref ref="example-poly-definite-integral" />,
	we split into two integrals,
	and then use
	<xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-split" text="type-local">Property</xref>
	of <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" />
	to re-base our integrals to match our formulas.
	<md>

		<mrow>
			\ccmint{3}{4}{ t + \frac{1}{t} }{t}
			\amp = \ccmint{3}{4}{t}{t} + \ccmint{3}{4}{\frac{1}{t}}{t}
		</mrow>

		<mrow>
			\amp =
			\left(
				\ccmint{0}{4}{t}{t}
				- \ccmint{0}{3}{t}{t}
			\right)
			+ \left(
				\ccmint{1}{4}{\frac{1}{t}}{t}
				- \ccmint{1}{3}{\frac{1}{t}}{t}
			\right)
		</mrow>

		<mrow>
			\amp =
			\left( \frac{4^2}{2} - \frac{3^2}{2} \right)
			+ ( \ln 4 - \ln 3 )
		</mrow>

		<mrow> \amp = \frac{7}{2} + \ln \left(\frac{4}{3}\right) </mrow>

	</md>
	</p>
</example>

<remark><p>
	It might seem like <q>cheating</q> to write <m>\ln 4</m> as the value of
	<me> \ccmint{1}{4}{\frac{1}{t}}{t} </me>,
	since <xref ref="definition-log-natural" /> says that to calculate <m>\ln 4</m> we would need to calculate that very integral
	(and similarly for <m>\ln 3</m>).
	But this is an acceptable way to represent the value of this integral,
	as there are several ways to numerically approximate values of the natural logarithm <mdash />
	using Riemann sums, for example.
	Your calculator even has a <m>\ln</m> button.
</p></remark>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-log-props">
<title>Properties of the natural logarithm</title>

<p>
First, our convention about integrating over a time interval of length <m>0</m>
leads immediately to a special value of the natural logarithm.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-log-value-at-1">
	<title>Logarithm at <m>t = 1</m></title>

	<statement><p> We have <me> \ln 1 = 0 </me>. </p> </statement>

	<proof><p>
		Combining <xref ref="convention-integ-definite-props-zero-length" text="type-local">Property</xref>
		of <xref ref="convention-integ-definite-props" />
		with <xref ref="definition-log-natural" />,
		<me> \ln 1 = \ccmint{1}{1}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} = 0 </me>.
	</p></proof>

</identity>

<p> Next, we note the domain of the natural logarithm. </p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-log-domain">
	<title>Domain of the natural logarithm</title>

	<statement><p>
		The value of <m>\ln t</m> is defined for all <m>t \gt 0</m> and undefined for all <m>t \le 0</m>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		Since the graph of our rate function <m>r(t) = 1/t</m> used to define the natural logarithm is continuous on <m>t \gt 0</m>,
		that rate function is integrable on any (finite) subdomain of <m>t \gt 0</m>.
		However, given our <q>initial</q> point at <m>t = 1</m> in the integration defining the logarithm,
		any second domain endpoint that lies in <m>t \le 0</m> will cause the singularity of <m>r(t)</m> at <m>t = 0</m> to be included,
		resulting in an integral that cannot be computed.
	</p></proof>

</identity>

<p>
From the graph of the logarithm function
(see <xref ref="figure-log-positive-values-height" /> or <xref ref="figure-log-negative-values-height" />),
we can see obvious long-term and singular behaviour.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-log-limits">
	<title>Long-term and singular behaviour of the natural logarithm</title>

	<statement><p><ol>

		<li><title>Long-term behaviour</title><p>
			As <m>t \to \infty</m>, also <m>\ln t \to \infty</m>.
		</p></li>

		<li><title>Singular behaviour</title><p>
			As <m>t \to 0^+</m>, <m>\ln t \to -\infty</m>.
		</p></li>

	</ol></p></statement>

</identity>

<p>
There are also a few algebraic patterns to the logarithm function that are not immediately obvious from its graph or from its definition as an accumulation function.
The first involves the logarithm of a product of two numbers.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-log-product">
	<title>Logarithm of a product</title>

	<statement><p>
		For all positive <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
		we have <me> \ln (a b) = \ln a + \ln b </me>.
		In other words, <em>the logarithm of a product is the sum of the logarithms</em>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof>

		<p>
		By definition, <me> \ln (a b) = \ccmint{1}{a b}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </me>.
		Using <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-split" text="type-local">Property</xref>
		of <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" />,
		we may write
		<md>
			<mrow> \ccmint{1}{a b}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} \amp = \ccmint{1}{a}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} + \ccmint{a}{a b}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \ln a + \ccmint{a}{a b}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </mrow>
		</md>.
		So we already have the first part of our desired formula, <m>\ln a</m>.
		What about the second integral
		<md><mrow xml:id="equation-log-product-second-int" tag="star"> \ccmint{a}{a b}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </mrow></md>?
		How does it compare to <me> \ln b = \ccmint{1}{b}{\frac{1}{s}}{s} </me>?
		(We have changed the integration variable to help keep things separate during our comparison of these two integrals.)
		It appears that the domain in integral <xref ref="equation-log-product-second-int" /> has been stretched by a factor of <m>a</m>
		compared to the domain in the integral defining <m>\ln b</m>.
		Remember that an integral is a calculation of (oriented) area under a graph,
		added up <q>slice by slice</q>
		(see <xref ref="figure-integ-representative-rect-slice" />).
		For each <q>slice</q> at position <m>s</m> in the integral for <m>\ln b</m>,
		we can create a corresponding <q>stretched slice</q> at position <m>u = a s</m>,
		where if <m>1 \le s \le b</m> then also <m>a \le a s \le a b</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="figure-log-slice-product">
			<caption>A slice of the area defining <m>\ln b</m> transforms into a slice of the area corresponding to integral <xref ref="equation-log-product-second-int" />.</caption>
			<sbsgroup>
				<sidebyside width="40%"><figure xml:id="figure-log-slice-product-ln-value">
					<caption>A representative slice of area in the integral defining <m>\ln b</m>.</caption>
					<image>
						<description>A representative slice of area in the integral defining a natural logarithm value.</description>
						<latex-image><xi:include href="log.d/slice-log-product.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
					</image>
				</figure></sidebyside>
				<sidebyside width="60%"><figure xml:id="figure-log-slice-product-scaled">
					<caption>A representative slice of area in integral <xref ref="equation-log-product-second-int" />.</caption>
					<image>
						<description>A representative slice of area in an integral related to the natural logarithm.</description>
						<latex-image><xi:include href="log.d/slice-log-product-scaled.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
					</image>
				</figure></sidebyside>
			</sbsgroup>
		</figure>

		<p>
		Because we are stretching horizontally by a factor of <m>a</m>,
		the slice at position <m>u</m> on the second graph will also be wider by a factor of <m>a</m>:
		<me> du = a ds </me>.
		But we are only transforming our <em>domain</em> values,
		we are not actually stretching our rate graph.
		So the slice at <m>u</m> has both a different width and a different height compared to the original slice at position <m>s</m>,
		since we have moved to a different place on the rate graph:
		<me> r(u) = \frac{1}{u} = \frac{1}{a s} = \frac{r(s)}{a} </me>.
		However, when calculate the <q>area</q> of this <q>stretched slice</q>,
		we find it's the same area as the slice at position <m>s</m> for the <m>\ln b</m> integral:
		<me> r(u) \intspace du = \left( \frac{r(s)}{a} \right) \left( a \intspace ds \right) = r(s) \intspace ds </me>.
		So as we add up <q>slices</q> of area to compute the integral for <m>\ln b</m>,
		or we add up <q>slices</q> of area to compute integral <xref ref="equation-log-product-second-int" />,
		we will be adding up the <em>same values</em> for those slices of area at corresponding positions,
		and so we will come out to the same total area:
		<me> \ccmint{a}{a b}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} = \ccmint{1}{b}{\frac{1}{s}}{s} = \ln b </me>,
		and thus
		<me> \ln (a b) = \ccmint{1}{a}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} + \ccmint{a}{a b}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} = \ln a + \ln b </me>.
		</p>

	</proof>

</identity>

<remark><p>
	We can be a little more precise in our justification above by considering actual Riemann sums of rectangular areas when we compare integral <xref ref="equation-log-product-second-int" /> with the integral for <m>\ln b</m>.
	What our <q>corresponding slices</q> argument essentially shows is that for each Riemann sum approximating the integral for <m>\ln b</m>,
	we can create a Riemann sum approximating integral <xref ref="equation-log-product-second-int" /> that computes to the same value.
	So the pattern of upper and lower sums squeezing down to the value for the integral for <m>\ln b</m> must be the same as the pattern of upper and lower sums squeezing down to the value of integral <xref ref="equation-log-product-second-int" />.
</p></remark>

<p>
So the logarithm turns a product into a sum.
What does it do to a reciprocal?
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-log-reciprocal">
	<title>Logarithm of a reciprocal</title>

	<statement><p>
		For all positive <m>a</m>,
		we have <me> \ln (1 / a) = - \ln a </me>.
		In other words, <em>the logarithm of a reciprocal is the negative of the logarithm</em>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof>

		<p>
		This time we will deal with an actual rectangular area in a typical Riemann sum,
		instead of just working with <q>slices</q>.
		For the integral
		<me> \ln a = \ccmint{1}{a}{\frac{1}{s}}{s} </me>,
		consider a typical rectangle at sample point <m>s</m> in an <em>upper sum</em> approximation.
		Because of the shape of the graph of the rate function,
		this sample point will appear at the left endpoint of the base of the rectangular area.
		Mark the right endpoint as <m>s'</m>,
		so that <me> \change{s} = s' - s </me>
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="figure-log-slice-recip-before">
			<caption>A representative rectangular area in a Riemann sum approximating <m>\ln a</m>.</caption>
			<image width="60%">
				<description>A representative rectangular area in a Riemann sum approximating the integral defining a natural logarithm value.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="log.d/rect-log.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
		By taking reciprocals,
		we can create a <q>mirror-image</q> rectangular base between <m>u' = 1 / s'</m> and <m>u = 1 / s</m>.
		To create a rectangle that represents a typical rectangle in an <em>upper</em> sum approximation of the integral
		<md><mrow xml:id="equation-log-reciprocal-int" tag="dstar"> \ccmint{1 / a}{1}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </mrow></md>,
		we'll take the sample point to be at <m>u'</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="figure-log-slice-recip-after">
			<caption>A representative rectangular area in a Riemann sum approximating integral <xref ref="equation-log-reciprocal-int" />.</caption>
			<image width="60%">
				<description>A representative rectangular area in a Riemann sum approximating an integral related to the natural logarithm.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="log.d/rect-log-recip.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<p>
		To relate the areas of these two rectangles,
		first calculate
		<md>
			<mrow> \change{u} \amp = u - u' </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{s} - \frac{1}{s'} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{s' - s}{s s'} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{s s'} \, \change{s} </mrow>
		</md>.
		So the area of the rectangle in <xref ref="figure-log-slice-recip-after" /> is
		<md>
			<mrow> r(u') \, \change{u} \amp = \frac{1}{u'} \cdot (u - u') </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{1 / s'} \cdot \frac{1}{s s'} \, \change{s} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{s} \change{s} </mrow>
		</md>,
		which is exactly equal to the area of the rectangle in <xref ref="figure-log-slice-recip-before" />.
		</p>

		<p>
		By matching up areas of rectangles in this way,
		we see that the two upper sum approximations would compute to the same total approximate area.
		That is,
		every upper sum approximation for the integral defining <m>\ln a</m> corresponds to an upper sum approximation for integral <xref ref="equation-log-reciprocal-int" /> with the same value.
		This would also work the other way <mdash />
		every upper sum approximation for integral <xref ref="equation-log-reciprocal-int" /> could be <q>flipped</q> over by taking reciprocals of the rectangle base boundary points to create an upper sum approximation for the integral defining <m>\ln a</m>.
		And by changing sample points,
		we would see the same correspondence for <em>lower</em> sum approximations of these two integrals.
		</p>

		<p>
		Therefore, the patterns of upper and lower sum approximations for each integral would <q>squeeze</q> down to the same values.
		That is, <me> \ccmint{1}{a}{\frac{1}{s}}{s} = \ccmint{1 / a}{1}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </me>.
		The first integral is the value of <m>\ln a</m>,
		while the second integral is the value of <m>- \ln (1 / a)</m>,
		using <xref ref="convention-integ-definite-props-backwards" text="type-local">Property</xref> of <xref ref="convention-integ-definite-props" />.
		Flipping the negative sign to the other side of the equality of integrals above,
		we obtain <me> \ln (1 / a) = - \ln a </me>, as desired.
		</p>

	</proof>

</identity>

<p>
We could rewrite <xref ref="pattern-log-reciprocal" /> as
<me> \ln (a^{-1}) = - \ln a </me>.
Using <xref ref="pattern-log-product" />,
we also have
<md alignment="gather">
	<mrow> \ln (a^2) = \ln (a \cdot a) = \ln a + \ln a </mrow>
	<mrow> \implies \ln (a^2) = 2 \ln a </mrow>
</md>.
In both instances we see an <em>exponent-becomes-coefficient</em> pattern.
Though we are not yet prepared to justify it,
in fact this pattern holds for all exponents.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-log-power">
	<title>Logarithm of a power</title>
	<p>
	For all exponents <m>r</m> and all positive bases <m>a</m>,
	we have <me> \ln (a ^ r) = r \ln a </me>.
	In other words, <em>the logarithm of a power is a multiple of the logarithm</em>.
	</p>
</identity>

<p>
Finally,
we can combine <xref ref="pattern-log-product" /> and <xref ref="pattern-log-reciprocal" />.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-log-quotient">
	<title>Logarithm of a quotient</title>
	<p>
	For all positive <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
	we have <me> \ln (a / b) = \ln a - \ln b </me>.
	In other words, <em>the logarithm of a quotient is the difference of the logarithms</em>.
	</p>
</identity>

</section>

